- Wed 22 Aug 2018. Ebola virus disease - Democratic Republic of Congo, WHO/AFRO external situation report 03
[WHO AFRO Outbreaks <afrooutbreak@who.int>, edited]
http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/274258/SITREP_EVD_DRC_20180820-eng.pdf

Situation overview
------------------
The Ministry of Health in the Democratic Republic of the Congo, WHO, and partners are responding to an Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak since 1 Aug 2018, with the epicentre being Mangina town in Mabalako health zone, North Kivu province, in the east of the country. Confirmed cases have also been reported from Beni health zone (North Kivu province) and Mandima health zone (Ituri province).

Since our last situation report on 14 Aug 2018 (External situation report 02; [see archive no. 20180815.5966397]), an additional 45 new confirmed EVD cases and 18 new deaths have been reported. 9 other suspected cases are under investigation to confirm or exclude EVD. By 20 Aug 2018, 39 case-patients were admitted in Ebola treatment centres (ETCs) in Mabalako (36) and Beni (3).

As of 20 Aug 2018, a total of 102 [MoH report states 103] confirmed and probable EVD cases, including 59 deaths, have been reported. Of the 102 cases, 75 are confirmed [MoH report states 76] and 27 are probable. Of the 59 deaths, 32 occurred in confirmed cases and 27 remain probable. A total of 13 cases have been reported among health workers, of which, 12 are confirmed and one has died. Since the onset of the outbreak, a total of 10 case-patients have recovered from the disease and were discharged and re-integrated into their communities. Among the 88 cases out of the 102 confirmed and probable cases for which age and sex are known, the median age was 32 years (age range: 0-74), with the age group 30-39 being most affected, accounting for 28 percent (25/88) cases. Women accounted for 58 percent (51/88) of all cases.

The epicentre of the outbreak remains Mabalako health zone in North Kivu province, reporting 80 percent (82) of all cases, including 61 confirmed and 21 probable cases. Additionally, 4 other health zones in North Kivu province and one in Ituri province have reported confirmed and probable cases (Table 1 -- Confirmed, probable and suspected Ebola virus disease cases by health zones in North Kivu and Ituri provinces, Democratic Republic of the Congo, as of 20 Aug 2018 [available at the source URL above]).

As of 20 Aug 2018, a total of 2408 contacts were listed, of these, 637 completed their 21-day mandatory follow up period. A total of 1782 are currently under surveillance, of which 1686 (95 percent) were seen on the reporting day.

The Ministry of Health, WHO and partners are monitoring and investigating alerts in other provinces in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and in neighbouring countries. Since the last report was published, alerts were investigated in several provinces of the Democratic Republic of the Congo as well as in Uganda, Rwanda, and the Central African Republic, and, to date, EVD has been ruled out in all these alerts.

Context
-------
[...]

The Democratic Republic of the Congo is also experiencing multiple disease outbreaks, including 3 separate outbreaks of circulating vaccine-derived poliovirus type 2 (cVDPV2) in the provinces of Mongola, Maniema, and Haut Lomami/Tanganyika/Haut Katanga/Ituri, cholera in 12 provinces, measles spread across the country, and monkeypox.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[As we observed during the recent Equateur province outbreak, these WHO/AFRO situation reports come out weekly and thus cannot provide up-to-the-minute case statistics, but they do provide excellent multi-color tables, maps, and graphs, together with bullet-point summaries of all key epidemic control activities. - Mod.LXL

With the focus on Ebola, one can easily lose sight of the multitude of other health issues in the DRC, as listed in the Context section above. The ability to care for patients infected with Ebola and these other pathogens is sadly compromised by the loss of health care workers battling the outbreak. But offering free health care to all as discussed in yesterday's ProMED-mail post (Ebola update (74): Congo DR (NK) cases, response, WHO, reflections 20180822.5979052) will bring individuals into the clinics who are sick and otherwise might not seek attention. This should help diminish spread of transmissible pathogens. Furthermore, it will assist in wound treatment from the unrest, helping to restore health to the community. - Mod.LK

Maps of DR Congo: http://goo.gl/DM2AT8 and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5981519,194]

